<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="159" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,150,977]" pageId="7" pageNumber="159">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,221,247]" pageId="7" pageNumber="159">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Female (
<figureCitation box="[425,507,221,248]" captionStart="FIGURES 16–24" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1903,1927]" captionTargetBox="[153,1437,479,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-183@6.[151,1437,475,1880]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 16–24. Hylomesa longiceps, ♀. 16. Habitus, dorsal view; 17. Head, frontal view; 18. Vertex, dorsal view; 19. Prono- tum, dorsal view; 20. Pronotum, lateral view; 21. Hind femur and tibia, dorsal view; 22. Propodeum, dorsal view; 23. T1, dorsal view; 24. T6, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641328" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641328/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="159">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
). Length of head (
<figureCitation box="[710,790,221,247]" captionStart="FIGURES 16–24" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1903,1927]" captionTargetBox="[153,1437,479,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-183@6.[151,1437,475,1880]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 16–24. Hylomesa longiceps, ♀. 16. Habitus, dorsal view; 17. Head, frontal view; 18. Vertex, dorsal view; 19. Prono- tum, dorsal view; 20. Pronotum, lateral view; 21. Hind femur and tibia, dorsal view; 22. Propodeum, dorsal view; 23. T1, dorsal view; 24. T6, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641328" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641328/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="159">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
) subequal (0.94–1.0×) to width in dorsal view, posterolateral angles rounded; clypeus (
<figureCitation box="[488,570,256,282]" captionStart="FIGURES 16–24" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1903,1927]" captionTargetBox="[153,1437,479,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-183@6.[151,1437,475,1880]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 16–24. Hylomesa longiceps, ♀. 16. Habitus, dorsal view; 17. Head, frontal view; 18. Vertex, dorsal view; 19. Prono- tum, dorsal view; 20. Pronotum, lateral view; 21. Hind femur and tibia, dorsal view; 22. Propodeum, dorsal view; 23. T1, dorsal view; 24. T6, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641328" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641328/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="159">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
) with weak carina on basal half or two-thirds; lower half of frons with dense punctures and upper half with sparse punctures; anteriorly one-third of vertex (
<figureCitation box="[1035,1116,291,317]" captionStart="FIGURES 16–24" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1903,1927]" captionTargetBox="[153,1437,479,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-183@6.[151,1437,475,1880]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 16–24. Hylomesa longiceps, ♀. 16. Habitus, dorsal view; 17. Head, frontal view; 18. Vertex, dorsal view; 19. Prono- tum, dorsal view; 20. Pronotum, lateral view; 21. Hind femur and tibia, dorsal view; 22. Propodeum, dorsal view; 23. T1, dorsal view; 24. T6, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641328" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641328/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="159">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
) with a few dense punctures and posterior two-thirds almost impunctate; OOD 2.17–2.43× POD, and 0.42–0.44× OCD, anterior ocellus closer to apex of antennal tubercles than to occiput; pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[779,859,360,386]" captionStart="FIGURES 16–24" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1903,1927]" captionTargetBox="[153,1437,479,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-183@6.[151,1437,475,1880]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 16–24. Hylomesa longiceps, ♀. 16. Habitus, dorsal view; 17. Head, frontal view; 18. Vertex, dorsal view; 19. Prono- tum, dorsal view; 20. Pronotum, lateral view; 21. Hind femur and tibia, dorsal view; 22. Propodeum, dorsal view; 23. T1, dorsal view; 24. T6, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641328" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641328/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="159">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
) anteriorly with strong carina, the anterior half with dense punctures, posterior half with very sparse and small punctures; lateral side (
<figureCitation box="[1087,1170,395,421]" captionStart="FIGURES 16–24" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1903,1927]" captionTargetBox="[153,1437,479,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-183@6.[151,1437,475,1880]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 16–24. Hylomesa longiceps, ♀. 16. Habitus, dorsal view; 17. Head, frontal view; 18. Vertex, dorsal view; 19. Prono- tum, dorsal view; 20. Pronotum, lateral view; 21. Hind femur and tibia, dorsal view; 22. Propodeum, dorsal view; 23. T1, dorsal view; 24. T6, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641328" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641328/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="159">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
) of pronotum ventrally with dense striae; propodeum (
<figureCitation box="[498,580,429,455]" captionStart="FIGURES 16–24" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1903,1927]" captionTargetBox="[153,1437,479,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-183@6.[151,1437,475,1880]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 16–24. Hylomesa longiceps, ♀. 16. Habitus, dorsal view; 17. Head, frontal view; 18. Vertex, dorsal view; 19. Prono- tum, dorsal view; 20. Pronotum, lateral view; 21. Hind femur and tibia, dorsal view; 22. Propodeum, dorsal view; 23. T1, dorsal view; 24. T6, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641328" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641328/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="159">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
) with broad median groove, and base of groove much wider than apex, near median groove with shallow and minute punctures and almost smooth, ventral surface of hind femur (
<figureCitation box="[1295,1377,464,490]" captionStart="FIGURES 16–24" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1903,1927]" captionTargetBox="[153,1437,479,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-183@6.[151,1437,475,1880]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 16–24. Hylomesa longiceps, ♀. 16. Habitus, dorsal view; 17. Head, frontal view; 18. Vertex, dorsal view; 19. Prono- tum, dorsal view; 20. Pronotum, lateral view; 21. Hind femur and tibia, dorsal view; 22. Propodeum, dorsal view; 23. T1, dorsal view; 24. T6, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641328" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641328/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="159">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
) medially with obtuse and short prominence; T1 (
<figureCitation box="[672,755,499,525]" captionStart="FIGURES 16–24" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1903,1927]" captionTargetBox="[153,1437,479,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-183@6.[151,1437,475,1880]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 16–24. Hylomesa longiceps, ♀. 16. Habitus, dorsal view; 17. Head, frontal view; 18. Vertex, dorsal view; 19. Prono- tum, dorsal view; 20. Pronotum, lateral view; 21. Hind femur and tibia, dorsal view; 22. Propodeum, dorsal view; 23. T1, dorsal view; 24. T6, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641328" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641328/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="159">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
) with anteriorly strong carina, behind the carina with dense punctures, wholly with sparse punctures and even almost impunctate, subapical groove indistinct; anterior half of T6 (
<figureCitation box="[197,278,568,594]" captionStart="FIGURES 16–24" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1903,1927]" captionTargetBox="[153,1437,479,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-183@6.[151,1437,475,1880]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 16–24. Hylomesa longiceps, ♀. 16. Habitus, dorsal view; 17. Head, frontal view; 18. Vertex, dorsal view; 19. Prono- tum, dorsal view; 20. Pronotum, lateral view; 21. Hind femur and tibia, dorsal view; 22. Propodeum, dorsal view; 23. T1, dorsal view; 24. T6, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641328" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641328/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="159">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
) with sparse and minute punctures, medial half with moderate to dense and deep punctures and apically impunctate and coriaceous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,150,977]" pageId="7" pageNumber="159">
Male. Clypeus with strong carina at basal two-thirds or three-fourths; length of head 0.85–0.87× width; frons largely with dense punctures; vertex with comparatively smaller and sparser punctures; OOD 1.9–2.8× POD, and 0.59–0.71× OCD; pronotum anteriorly strongly carinate, behind the carina with weak to strong and dense punctures (some contiguous) in a few transverse grooves; propodeum irregularly reticulate, and with narrow median groove containing a few transverse striae, dorsum with bordering carina between horizontal and posterior surfaces; lateral side of propodeum anteriorly with a few strong striae, the rest of surface with coarse and dense punctures or irregularly reticulate; T1 anteriorly with strongly transverse carina and with sparse punctures. No male specimens were collected in our study, and the description is referred to 
<bibRefCitation author="Krombein, K. V." box="[775,970,880,907]" pageId="7" pageNumber="159" pagination="1 - 22" refId="ref16501" refString="Krombein, K. V. (1968) Studies in the Tiphiidae. 10. Hylomesa, a new genus of myzinine wasp parasitic on larvae of longicorn beetles (Hymenoptera). Proceedings of the United States National Museum, 124 (3644), 1 - 22. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00963801.124 - 3644.1" type="journal article" year="1968">Krombein (1968)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Turner, R. E." box="[1024,1185,880,907]" pageId="7" pageNumber="159" pagination="86 - 96" refId="ref17347" refString="Turner, R. E. (1918) Notes on Fossorial Hymenoptera, XXXII: On New Species in the British Museum. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 9, 1, 86 - 96. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222931808562292" type="journal article" year="1918">Turner (1918)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
